From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keyur Maru <kd2maru@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 13 Jul 2026 02:15:47 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 1/4] freedreno/drm: let the winsys backend gate fence
 retirement

cleanup_fences() drops a bo's fence as soon as the shared control->fence has
caught up with that fence's ufence.  fd_bo_state() then reports the bo IDLE
and the bo-cache is free to hand it to a new allocation.

That is only correct if control->fence is authoritative for "the GPU is done
with this batch".  On the downstream KGSL kernel interface it is not:
control->fence is written by the GPU's CACHE_FLUSH_TS event, which can advance
before the batch has actually retired.  The bo-cache then recycles a buffer the
GPU is still writing, those writes land in the buffer's new owner, and the
result is silent corruption (garbled tiles and icons under UI scroll) with no
page fault to point at the culprit.

Add an optional fd_pipe_funcs.retired(pipe, kfence) predicate, consulted before
a fence is pruned, which lets a backend answer the question authoritatively --
on KGSL by reading the per-context end-of-pipeline RETIRED timestamp.  It is
left NULL on msm and virtio, where control->fence is authoritative and
behaviour is unchanged.

kfence is guaranteed to be set by the time cleanup_fences() can reach this
check: control->fence only reaches ufence once the submit has been flushed to
the kernel, which is where kfence is stamped.
---
 src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_bo.c   | 14 ++++++++++++++
 src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_priv.h |  8 ++++++++
 2 files changed, 22 insertions(+)

diff --git a/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_bo.c b/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_bo.c
index 6eda810..00bbac0 100644
--- a/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_bo.c
+++ b/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_bo.c
@@ -767,6 +767,20 @@ cleanup_fences(struct fd_bo *bo)
       if (fd_fence_before(f->pipe->control->fence, f->ufence))
          continue;
 
+      /* channel A17 (KGSL bo-cache recycle fix): control->fence is written by
+       * the GPU's CACHE_FLUSH_TS event, which on KGSL advances before the batch
+       * has truly retired.  Pruning here would let fd_bo_state() report the bo
+       * IDLE and the bo-cache hand a still-in-flight buffer to a new allocation,
+       * so the GPU's pending writes land in the recycled buffer -> icon/tile
+       * corruption with no page fault.  When the backend exposes the kernel
+       * RETIRED timestamp (KGSL), require it to have passed f->kfence before
+       * pruning; no-op (NULL) on msm/virtio where control->fence is
+       * authoritative.  kfence is guaranteed set here: control->fence only
+       * reaches ufence after the submit was flushed to the kernel, which is
+       * where kfence is stamped. */
+      if (f->pipe->funcs->retired && !f->pipe->funcs->retired(f->pipe, f->kfence))
+         continue;
+
       bo->nr_fences--;
 
       if (bo->nr_fences > 0) {
diff --git a/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_priv.h b/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_priv.h
index 3a243b6..3deabe4 100644
--- a/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_priv.h
+++ b/src/freedreno/drm/freedreno_priv.h
@@ -310,6 +310,14 @@ struct fd_pipe_funcs {
                     uint64_t value);
    int (*wait)(struct fd_pipe *pipe, const struct fd_fence *fence,
                uint64_t timeout);
+   /* channel A17 (KGSL): optional predicate returning true iff the GPU has
+    * actually retired kfence.  On KGSL the shared control->fence (written by the
+    * GPU's CACHE_FLUSH_TS event) can advance before the batch truly retires, so
+    * cleanup_fences() consults this before pruning a fence - otherwise
+    * fd_bo_state() would report a still-in-flight bo IDLE and the bo-cache would
+    * recycle it under the GPU, corrupting the reused buffer.  Left NULL on
+    * backends (msm/virtio) where control->fence is authoritative. */
+   bool (*retired)(struct fd_pipe *pipe, uint32_t kfence);
    void (*destroy)(struct fd_pipe *pipe);
 };
 
